text: If you look closely at these "remakes" it really shows how much deeper people of this generation think. It shows how back in the 80's it was okay to make a movie with just explosions and cool one-liners and have it instantly become a cult classic. But movies nowadays delve into deeper issues such as the ethics, and the "human element", and what happens when the human spirit mixes with a cold calculating program. The original Robocop just blew shit up and killed all the baddies (and even a SUPERVILLAIN) and he was heralded for it. Nowadays movies really have to make you think to leave an actual impression.

text: This movie is good. I liked the first RoboCop and thought this one would be terrible. But they focus on different things. The first is really violent, and RoboCop is almost non human. On the second, he uses non lethal weapons to deal with most threats (which is modern) and he is actually trying to stay alive (not loosing his conscience and becoming a money making projext for Omnicorp). He still runs after the bad guys, but this movie places the bad guys in the top of society, running all the way to the bottom. Yet that violent, out of control social framing of the first movie is gone. Detroid doesn't seems that bad. The music is bad also, doesn't help to create the mood. Yet, the actors are good, saving for Samuel's performance which is hilarious and good.

author: Emmanuel Oxendine

text: The remake (which I just watched today) just doesnt have the cold gritty feel of the original. The characters dont have as much impact. that clarence guy in the original is scary as hell and the scene where they torture Murphy always gets my heart pounding.  Its such a build up while Murphy tracks the gang down, and of course the scene in the construction yard when he gets that spike in his neck. Man the original had some serious balls. The remake is just too flashy and action focused, it doesnt have any of the dark, gritty violence or atmosphere of the original. I dont think the remake is the worst remake i've ever seen, its still a lot better than the shitty Total Recall remake. Shame they always have to go for the PG13 rating. The Dredd remake is the only remake released in years which actually has the guts to make it gritty.  I didnt like how the remake focused more on his family. I thought it was better in the original when they pretty much brought him back as a machine and his human soul is still alive and trying to regain some memories and his family assume he's dead. It feels like that was just too cold for the remake. The remake feels more like a remake of Inspector Gadget than Robocop.
